text:

Feel free to check out the code and point out the mistakes or leave suggestions. I am newbie programmer :)

Patent/copyright research for a mobile application idea. Inbox
text:
if anyone allow to share your opinion on the necessity of conducting patent/copyright research for a mobile application idea BEFORE design, prototype, testing, proposal etc.

I have an idea for a mobile application with some features & functions that can't be found in some mobile applications, but I concern whether they have been patented/copyrighted. If people had known something had been copyrighted/patented, of course people wouldn't wanted to develop it, not only it is a waste of time to develop things have been patented/copyrighted but also it might end up getting themselves in infringement lawsuit.

Would you recommend entrepreneurs should prioritize patent/copyright research for features & functions they wanted to build or entrepreneurs are not encouraged to spend on hiring a patent drafter specialist?

text:

I am starting my side hustle and came up with the idea of creating an app that would suggest ideas for dating with your partner. I've always faced that problem and feel like it's something I could try to solve.

Currently starting to build the app and at the same time checking the feasibility of the idea and would be happy to hear your opinions on that.

Have you ever faced the same problem? If so, what would you like to have in the app that solves it?

Ask HN: How to motivate a parent to learn CS?
text:
With all the software and AI revolution, programming is so a basic need yet most people don't understand how Internet, computers, and software "really works" nor they do want to know or "have the time". But it's freaking important, aren't we all gonna explode if society is divided into the lucky tech "elite" and the plebe?

I know some parents in their 50s that could have had a computer and manual to code (BASIC, etc.) but didn't get one in their childhood (instead they got barbies or some consummer midly interesting stuff, etc.) eventually and now they are embittered towards maths but think that they could have been computer experts.

How would you teach a dad or mom in their 50s with professional basic experience (office software) in Windows, MacOs (typic folks who grew up in the prosperous 70s/80s) and a little time to spare from time to time especially the weekend?

Let's imagine they have a brand new computer (laptop/deskotp on MacOS) and have very low patience but a bit of curiosity. (They aren't nerds at all but the 70s born vibe make them like fame and nostalgic about some things I guess).

thanks
